retrofit:HooksMainOnlyNoOp a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "pre-commit/pre-push hooks are main-only -- ACCEPTED, deliberate design" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:PullRequestPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "RE-CONFIRMED CURRENT 2026-07-21: scripts/hooks/pre-commit.sh lines 9-13 and pre-push.sh's equivalent both still silently exit 0 on any non-main branch. This is not undisclosed: CLAUDE.md's own 'Git Hooks & Build Gotchas' section documents this as deliberate ('deliberate, not a bug... feature-branch validation deferred to PR-time CI: ci.yml/quality.yml trigger on pull_request'), with the explicit consequence named ('a green git commit/git push on a feature branch carries no hook-provided guarantee -- just pre-commit/just check/just test must be run manually'). Bounded accepted risk: scope=local hook silence on feature branches only, failure consequence=a developer skipping manual just pre-commit before pushing (mitigated by real PR-time CI enforcement), owner=documented in CLAUDE.md, review trigger=if PR-time CI itself is ever found to have a gap this silence could hide." .

retrofit:ReleaseGateBrokenForWeeks a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "release.yml audit gate -- RESOLVED: full workflow observed genuinely green end to end, first time in this SPOF's history" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:ReleasePath ;
    retrofit:evidence "RESOLVED (root cause + fix), NOT YET CI-CONFIRMED, re-verified 2026-07-21: commit 53961f0ac / merged PR #349 identified the exact gate -- `cargo cicd status audit` hardcoded an OCEL evidence path but `wpm audit` only parses XES, so every release-workflow run refused with a format-mismatch error (confirmed against a real GH Actions run URL in that commit's own message). Live .github/workflows/release.yml now calls `wpm audit \"$XES\"` against the real events.xes sibling file, bypassing the OCEL-hardcoded path -- fix is committed and live. Kept Blocking, not restood Accepted, because that PR's own disclosed standing says a real green release.yml run post-fix is still required before this can claim Proven -- the fix is a workflow-file diff plus local reproduction, not that run. Next action: observe the next real release.yml execution; restand to Accepted only once a genuine green run is observed, not before." ;
    retrofit:evidenceUpdate2026_07_22 "CORRECTING the prior evidence's optimistic 'awaiting confirmation' framing with a real, contradicting observation, per no-overclaiming discipline: the OCEL/XES fix DID land and the format-mismatch failure mode is genuinely gone, but release.yml has NOT gone green -- `gh run list --workflow=release.yml --limit 5` shows 5/5 recent runs on main FAILED (2026-07-21T05:57Z through 2026-07-22T03:44Z), all in the SAME job/step: 'Release Health Check' > 'Process conformance gate (wpm oracle)'. Real log evidence from the most recent run (databaseId 29889224190, 2026-07-22T03:49:24Z): `wpm audit` itself now runs cleanly against real XES evidence (exit 0, confirming the OCEL/XES fix holds) and produces 'Audit Verdict: DECEPTIVE, Fitness Score: 0.0000, Precision Score: 1.0000, Total Traces Audited: 1, Deviating Traces: 1' with the sole sample deviation showing 'trace-0  0.00  M: 0, R: 0' (zero missing/remaining events, yet zero fitness) -- the gate's own bash then greps the lowercased output for 'deceptive' and exits 1 by design ('[REFUSE] DECEPTIVE -- event log does not prove a lawful process happened'). This is a NEW, different blocker from the one PR #349 fixed: a real conformance-checking defect (either in how release.yml's own workflow run generates its events.xes trace, or in the wpm oracle's model/oracle definition for what a 'lawful' release-workflow trace looks like) causing a single-trace audit to score 0 fitness with 0 named problems -- not yet root-caused by this pass (out of scope for CiIntegrationTestsNeverRun's closure; named precisely here rather than left silently unrestood). Standing correctly remains Blocking -- ReleasePath is still not provably working end-to-end." ;
    retrofit:evidenceUpdate2026_07_22b "ADDITIVE, DOES NOT RESOLVE THE DECEPTIVE/FITNESS-0.0 BLOCKER ABOVE: PR #416 (branch fix/release-gate-pin-external-deps, open, not yet merged -- correcting this entry's own earlier 'merged' overclaim) fixed a third, orthogonal problem found while investigating why this gate's apparent root cause kept shifting between sessions -- .github/actions/install-cargo-tools/action.yml installed both cargo-cicd and wasm4pm-cli (wpm) via `cargo install --git ... --branch main`, a floating ref. Since the release-health job's TRUTHFUL/VARIANCE/DECEPTIVE verdict (including the DECEPTIVE/fitness-0.0 result documented directly above) is computed entirely inside these two external, ggen-uncontrolled tools, a floating branch meant that verdict -- and whether the tool even compiled -- could change with zero corresponding ggen-side commit. Now pinned to named commits (cargo-cicd@852a2d965, wasm4pm@98541a5ff); each install reproduced successfully from a scratch CARGO_HOME/--root outside CI before pushing. This does NOT fix the DECEPTIVE verdict itself -- that logic lives in wasm4pm's own fitness/precision algorithms, out of bounds per this repo's own Process Intelligence Boundary rule (CLAUDE.md). What it buys: the DECEPTIVE/fitness-0.0 finding above is now reproducible against a fixed, named external commit instead of 'whatever wasm4pm@main happens to be during this workflow run' -- the actual prerequisite for the real root-cause work in the next update." ;
    retrofit:evidenceUpdate2026_07_22c "THE DECEPTIVE/FITNESS-0.0 BLOCKER ABOVE IS NOW ROOT-CAUSED AND FIXED (PR #419, branch fix/release-gate-degenerate-trace, open, not yet merged): using the pinned cargo-cicd@852a2d965/wasm4pm@98541a5ff revs from PR #416, reproduced the exact DECEPTIVE/0.0000/M:0,R:0 shape locally by running only `cargo cicd workspace doctor` in a scratch evidence dir. Root cause: that single command emits exactly ONE declared-model activity event ('workspace:doctor' complete) into events.xes -- cargo-cicd's evidence writer intentionally drops 'start' lifecycle events before building the XES (seanchatmangpt/cargo-cicd src/evidence.rs::emit_xes_impl, its own comment: 'they duplicate activity names and corrupt token replay fitness'). `wpm audit` self-discovers a Petri net/directly-follows graph FROM THAT SAME LOG and token-replays it against itself -- with only 1 event, the discovered model has zero real directly-follows edges, only a synthetic sink-consume transition whose postset is empty, so `produced` ends up exactly 0 while `consumed` is nonzero. wasm4pm's compute_fitness (wasm4pm/src/simd_token_replay.rs:375-384) only guards the case where BOTH consumed AND produced are 0 -- this asymmetric zero falls through to a 0.0/0.0 division, producing NaN, which serializes to JSON null and gets silently displayed as a literal '0.0000'/'M: 0, R: 0' by wpm-cli's own `.unwrap_or(0.0)` printer (wasm4pm-cli src/commands/audit.rs). Confirmed NOT a genuine conformance violation: running 3 more of cargo-cicd's own already-declared, read-only, side-effect-free diagnostic activities (status show / target show / test changed) in the SAME evidence session before the audit turns the trace into a real multi-activity one, and the identical `wpm audit` verdict flips to TRUTHFUL, Fitness 1.0000, Precision 1.0000, 1/1 fitting traces. Also ran the full step-chain reproduction (exact bash from both release.yml steps, copy-run in sequence): FINAL EXIT CODE 0. `test changed`'s git-diff-against-origin/main confirmed safe under this job's shallow, tag-only checkout (fetch-depth: 1, no origin/main ref present) by reading ChangedFileDetector::changed_rs_files directly -- it falls back to an empty diff on any git-command failure rather than erroring, and TestChangedVerb::run always emits a PASS event regardless of what it finds. `status audit` (separate, already-known OCEL-hardcoded-path bug) and `target prune`/`publish run` (destructive/release-adjacent) are deliberately excluded from the fix. This does not touch wasm4pm/cargo-cicd's own algorithm code, per the Process Intelligence Boundary rule -- it only runs more of the SAME evidence-emitting commands this workflow already trusted. Standing correctly remains Blocking: all three fixes (#349 merged and live, #416 and #419 open) are real and independently verified by local reproduction, but zero of them has yet been confirmed by an actual green release.yml run -- this repo's release.yml only triggers on tag push or workflow_dispatch, not on PR CI, so that confirmation can only come from the next real tagged release or a manual workflow_dispatch. Next action: after #416/#419 merge, trigger or await the next real release.yml run; restand to Accepted only once it is observed green." ;
    retrofit:evidenceUpdate2026_07_22d "#416 AND #419 BOTH MERGED; A REAL RELEASE.YML RUN CONFIRMS THE DECEPTIVE FIX HOLDS, THEN EXPOSES A NEW, DISTINCT, PREVIOUSLY-UNREACHABLE FAILURE: run 29911316089 (2026-07-22T10:17Z, headSha 2f85678b8, after both merges) shows job 'Release Health Check' -- SUCCESS. The DECEPTIVE-verdict blocker documented in evidenceUpdate2026_07_22/b/c is genuinely resolved; this is the first real evidence, not another local reproduction. But the workflow OVERALL still reports failure: 'Build Release' (all 4 platform targets) and every 'Cross-Host Repro' leg failed, each with the SAME error -- `error: could not execute process 'sccache ... rustc -vV' (never executed) ... No such file or directory`. Root cause (see PR #426, branch fix/release-build-job-missing-setup): both jobs used a bespoke dtolnay/rust-toolchain step (`toolchain: stable`, no sibling-repo provisioning, no sccache install) instead of the already-proven ./.github/actions/setup-ggen-build composite action every other CI job uses. Not a new defect -- a latent one, invisible until now because build-release's own `needs: [release-health]` gate blocked it behind the DECEPTIVE bug for as long as that bug existed; fixing evidenceUpdate2026_07_22c's finding is what let this run far enough to hit it for the first time. `toolchain: stable` is independently wrong too: setup-ggen-build's own STEP 2 comment states nightly-2026-06-22 (matching rust-toolchain.toml) is the only channel that compiles this workspace. PR #426 fixes both jobs -- build-release now reuses setup-ggen-build wholesale; build-release-repro gets the same two missing pieces (sibling provisioning + sccache) inlined verbatim rather than the full composite, since that job's entire premise is a truly cold, uncached build and the composite's own caching step would silently undermine that guarantee. Standing correctly remains Blocking: ReleasePath is closer to working than at any point in this SPOF's history (the actual conformance-gate defect is fixed and confirmed by a real run) but still not provably working end-to-end -- PR #426 is open, not yet merged, and its own fix has the same real-run-only verification limit as every fix before it. Next action: merge #426; observe the next real release.yml run; restand to Accepted only once Build Release and Cross-Host Repro are observed green, not merely Release Health Check." ;
    retrofit:evidenceUpdate2026_07_22f "RESTOOD TO ACCEPTED -- THE CONDITION NAMED IN EVERY PRIOR UPDATE IS NOW MET FOR REAL: PR #426 merged, then a real post-fix run (29915682895) surfaced two MORE previously-unreachable bugs (both root-caused and fixed in PR #432, branch fix/release-macos-bash3-compat -- macOS's system bash 3.2.57 has no associative-array support, breaking the sibling-provisioning script on every macOS-hosted job; and a genuinely dead `reqwest` runtime dependency in ggen-cli plus a workspace-wide reqwest spec that never disabled default-features, both compiling in native-tls/openssl-sys unnecessarily and breaking the aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu cross-compile). PR #432 merged 2026-07-22T12:19:41Z; the resulting semantic-release run (29919176631, success) tagged and dispatched a fresh release.yml run, databaseId 29919854272, completed 2026-07-22T12:58:09Z (real GH Actions run, not local reproduction). Every one of its 16 jobs succeeded: Release Health Check; all 4 Build Release targets (x86_64/aarch64 x apple-darwin/unknown-linux-gnu); all 8 Cross-Host Repro replicas (2 independent builds x 4 targets); and, for the first time ever, all 4 Verify Cross-Host Reproducibility jobs actually RAN (never reached in any prior run) and passed, confirming genuine byte-identical reproducibility across independently-provisioned build hosts for every release target. Five real, independently-verified fixes accumulated across this SPOF's history are now all confirmed live and sufficient together: PR #349 (OCEL/XES format-mismatch), PR #416 (dependency pinning), PR #419 (degenerate-trace DECEPTIVE bug), PR #426 (missing build-job setup), PR #432 (macOS bash 3.2 compat + openssl-sys elimination). retrofit:ReleasePath is provably working end-to-end, observed directly, not inferred. No further action required on this SPOF; a future regression would need its own fresh finding, not a reopening of this one." .

retrofit:BrokenJustSyncRecipes a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "just sync / just sync-dry recipes -- RESOLVED, original flags no longer exist" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:ReleasePath, retrofit:GenerationPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "RESOLVED, independently re-verified 2026-07-21: justfile's sync/sync-dry recipes (lines 414-419) already invoke `{{GGEN}} sync run` / `{{GGEN}} sync run --dry-run` -- not the `--audit`/`--dry_run true` flags this SPOF's original evidence cited, which no longer appear anywhere in the recipe. Confirmed live: `just sync-dry` runs, hits zero flag-parsing errors, and fails only on the separate, already-tracked O-3/O-7 evidence-gate refusal (FM-LAW-018, byte-identity still red) -- a genuinely different, already-known condition, not this SPOF's original claim. CLAUDE.md's own prose still describes the old broken flags as current, which is now stale generated-doc content (a minor, separate doc-drift item, not re-opening this SPOF)." .

retrofit:PartialPublishRollbackUnknown a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "Partial-publish detection/rollback across 5 release targets -- CONFIRMED real gap" ;
    retrofit:standing "Blocking" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:ReleasePath ;
    retrofit:evidence "RE-VERIFIED 2026-07-21, restood Unknown->Blocking (this is now a confirmed absence, not an unchecked unknown): all 5 files (publish-registry.yml 90 lines, publish-candidate.yml 107, homebrew-release.yml 121, release-debian.yml 169, docker-build-push.yml 282) read in full. publish-registry.yml/publish-candidate.yml have zero rollback/cleanup/failure-handling of any kind. homebrew-release.yml/release-debian.yml only post failure summaries or upload debug artifacts via if: failure()/always() -- no undo of already-published state. docker-build-push.yml's if: always() only uploads Trivy scan results. No cross-workflow coordination or partial-publish rollback mechanism exists anywhere. NOT fixed here: designing real cross-workflow rollback across 5 independent, differently-shaped release targets is a substantial, distinctly-scoped effort -- named as a future generation's obligation, not attempted this cycle given the volume of higher-priority work already closed." ;
    retrofit:evidenceUpdate2026_07_22 "REAL PREREQUISITE FINDING, standing correctly UNCHANGED (rollback itself still not built). Investigating this SPOF for a smaller first step surfaced that 3 of the 5 targets have been SILENTLY NON-FUNCTIONAL, not just unrolled-back-when-they-fail -- a rollback mechanism for targets that never successfully publish in the first place would be moot, so this is real, in-scope prerequisite work, not scope creep. Root-caused with real evidence (gh run/check-run annotations, not assumed) and fixed:\n\n(1) release-debian.yml: 10/10 visible runs failed identically with `Invalid pattern '../ggen_*.deb*'. Relative pathing is not allowed.` -- debuild conventionally builds .deb output one directory ABOVE the source package (confirmed: scripts/build-debian-package.sh's own Gate 10/11 read from `../ggen_*.deb*`), but actions/upload-artifact and softprops/action-gh-release both reject any `../` path. Fixed by staging the built .deb into the workspace root before referencing it. DISCLOSED, NOT fixed: the script also hardcodes `5.0.2-1_amd64` throughout rather than deriving the real version -- a separate, real footgun, left alone rather than risked in this same pass.\n\n(2) docker-build-push.yml: EVERY visible run (any branch, not just tags) shows zero jobs scheduled and `This run likely failed because of a workflow file issue` -- confirmed root cause by reading the file: `BUILD_DATE=${{ ... || now() }}` references `now()`, which is not a real GitHub Actions expression function, causing the whole file to fail schema validation at parse time before any trigger filter is even evaluated (explaining why it appeared to misfire on non-tag branches too). Fixed by using `github.run_started_at`, a real builtin context property, preserving the original fallback intent.\n\n(3) homebrew-release.yml: entire visible history is 3 runs, ALL predating or outside the current release.yml flow (v0.2.4/v5.0.0/v26.7.2) -- zero runs for any of the dozens of real v26.7.x releases since, despite every one of those releases genuinely existing, published (not draft), with all 4 binary assets attached (verified directly: `gh release view v26.7.43`). Root cause: `on: release: types: [published]` never fires for a release created via GITHUB_TOKEN -- the EXACT SAME class of suppression release.yml's own header comment already documented for tag pushes, just never checked for the release-published event. Fixed the same way release.yml's own tag-push suppression was fixed (a pattern already proven live in this exact repo, not invented here): release.yml now explicitly `gh workflow run`s homebrew-release.yml right after build-release completes (workflow_dispatch/repository_dispatch ARE the documented GITHUB_TOKEN exception); homebrew-release.yml gained a workflow_dispatch trigger with a tag input, and its version-extraction step now branches on event type so the pre-existing release-triggered path is untouched.\n\nHONEST LIMITATION, stated plainly per this repo's evidence-first discipline: none of these three fixes could be verified end-to-end via a real run in this pass. Unlike ci.yml (exercised by every PR), release.yml/release-debian.yml/docker-build-push.yml/homebrew-release.yml only run on real tag pushes or workflow_dispatch against a real tag -- and actually triggering one, or letting homebrew-release.yml's bump-homebrew-formula-action push to the real external seanchatmangpt/homebrew-tap repo, would be a real publish action, which this session is not authorized to trigger without an explicit `!` command. These are reasoned, evidence-grounded fixes (each backed by a real, quoted, previously-reproducing error), not yet observed green. Verification is deferred to the next naturally-occurring release cycle (the same discipline already applied to closing retrofit:ReleaseGateBrokenForWeeks) -- a future session should confirm via a real run before treating any of these 3 targets as trustworthy.\n\nStanding correctly remains Blocking: the SPOF's own named concern (partial-publish detection/rollback across the 5 targets) is still completely unaddressed -- what changed is that 3 of the 5 targets are no longer confirmed-broken by causes unrelated to rollback, a real but different-shaped contribution toward the same eventual goal." ;
    retrofit:evidenceUpdate2026_07_22b "DETECTION HALF BUILT (real, adversarially-verified), and NEW EVIDENCE that the underlying publish problem is DEEPER than PR #441 (merged) actually fixed -- standing correctly remains Blocking, for a stronger reason than before, not a weaker one.\n\nBuilt via a 5-phase multi-agent workflow (Understand x4 targets in parallel -> Design -> Implement -> Verify -> Adversarial x2 in parallel), all real gh/jq calls against live repo state, zero mutating actions anywhere (independently grepped for POST/PUT/DELETE/gh-release-create/gh-workflow-run/docker-push/git-push -- none found): scripts/ci/check-partial-publish.sh (the read-only detection engine, checks all 4 tag-correlated targets: release.yml via GitHub Release asset-list completeness, release-debian.yml via .deb asset presence + run correlation, docker-build-push.yml via per-job conclusion, homebrew-release.yml via the EXTERNAL seanchatmangpt/homebrew-tap Formula/ggen.rb version match -- the one check in the whole detector that reaches outside this repo's own API surface) and .github/workflows/detect-partial-publish.yml (workflow_run-triggered on completion of any of the 4 correlated workflows, so it self-corrects as async results land with no polling/sleep; GITHUB_STEP_SUMMARY output only, matching this repo's own established convention -- no issue filing, no notification, no retry). Real 3-state PASS/FAIL/PENDING verdict, never exits 1 on PENDING (a target that legitimately hasn't run yet is not a break).\n\nAdversarial review (independent agents, false-green and false-red lenses) found two real issues, one fixed in this pass and one disclosed:\n- FIXED: docker-build-push.yml's check gated PASS/FAIL on the WHOLE RUN's conclusion before ever inspecting per-job conclusions -- since that workflow's scan-images/sign-and-sbom jobs run AFTER the actual publish and can fail independently (concretely: cosign's keyless signing needs `id-token: write`, which the workflow does not grant -- a real, reproducing gap, not hypothetical), this was a genuine false-red: a real successful publish would have been reported FAIL. Fixed by always checking the two publish jobs' own conclusions when status=completed, falling back to the run-level conclusion only when zero jobs were ever scheduled (the workflow-file-parse-failure case). Re-verified against real v26.7.44/v26.7.2 data post-fix -- unchanged correct output, no regression.\n- DISCLOSED, not fixed: the asset-presence checks (release.yml, release-debian.yml) verify a filename exists on the GitHub Release but never download+compare content against GitHub's own computed digest field -- a build that succeeds at the process level while producing wrong bytes would read as PASS. Verifying this would require real network downloads of every asset, a materially bigger feature than the lightweight metadata GETs used everywhere else in this detector; deliberately not bundled into this first pass, stated plainly in the script's own header comment rather than hidden.\n\nReal, previously-unknown findings surfaced BY BUILDING the detector (not assumed, each independently gh-verified):\n- release-debian.yml has THREE independent bugs, not the one PR #441 fixed. Fetched the real v26.7.2 failure log (`gh run view 28626795809 --log-failed`): the build dies at its own Gate 2 (`debian/ directory not found`) BEFORE ever reaching the relative-path bug PR #441 fixed -- confirmed via `git ls-tree -r` on both origin/main and origin/fix/broken-publish-targets (now merged) that no `debian/` directory exists anywhere in this repo, at any commit checked. Separately, and more consequential: unlike release.yml and homebrew-release.yml, NO dispatch step was added anywhere for release-debian.yml -- it still relies solely on its native `push: tags` trigger, which is the same GITHUB_TOKEN-suppressed event class already fixed for the other two targets. Confirmed empirically: 15 total runs ever, all failure, none since 2026-07-02, despite dozens of real tags pushed since. Net effect: PR #441's fix to this target, while a real and correct fix to what it addressed, is necessary but NOT sufficient -- this target will most likely continue to silently never publish even now that PR #441 is merged.\n- docker-build-push.yml: the `now()` fix (PR #441, merged) makes the file parseable again, but does not make this target actually publish. Two independently-confirmed, pre-existing blockers remain untouched by that fix: `REGISTRY_GCP: artifacts.example.com` does not resolve (IANA documentation domain, not a real registry -- confirmed via dig/nslookup; the same placeholder also appears repo-wide in .github/CI_CD_PIPELINE.md, .github/CICD_IMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md, and semantic-release.yml), and `GCP_ARTIFACT_REGISTRY_KEY` does not exist as a repo secret at all (`gh api repos/.../actions/secrets` -> zero secrets configured). A real tag push after PR #441 will very likely still fail, now at the GCP login step instead of at YAML parse time.\n- homebrew-release.yml: directly confirmed the external tap formula (seanchatmangpt/homebrew-tap, Formula/ggen.rb) is still pinned to version 0.2.4, last touched 2025-10-10 -- independent, external confirmation this target has never actually delivered a real v26.7.x update to a real user-facing install path, consistent with PR #441's fix being real but, as of this evidence pass, not yet observed to have actually run.\n- RESOLVED AS A FALSE ALARM (not a new regression): the investigation initially flagged tags v26.8.0 through v26.15.1 as having empty (0-asset) releases and described them as \"newer than v26.7.44\" -- re-verified directly against the real chronological release history (`gh api repos/.../releases --paginate`, sorted by published_at, not semver): those tags were published 2026-07-18 through 2026-07-21, i.e. CHRONOLOGICALLY OLDER than v26.7.44 (published 2026-07-22T17:16:40Z) -- the version NUMBER briefly went as high as v26.15.1 then reset back down to a fresh v26.7.x sequence, an odd but separate observation about semantic-release's version calculation during the already-known broken period, not a live regression. The real chronological data shows a clean 2-asset -> 8-asset -> 8 -> 8 -> 8 progression from v26.7.40 onward, which is ADDITIONAL corroborating evidence for retrofit:ReleaseGateBrokenForWeeks's already-Accepted closure (4 consecutive full-success releases now, not just the 1 run originally cited), not a contradiction of it. No restand needed there; recorded here so a future session doesn't re-discover and re-panic on the same semver-vs-chronology confusion.\n\nStanding remains Blocking, now for a MORE PRECISE reason than the prior update: rollback is still entirely unbuilt (unchanged, correctly out of scope pending explicit human authorization per this SPOF's own hard constraint), AND detection now exists and is real, BUT 2 of the 4 tag-correlated targets (release-debian.yml, docker-build-push.yml) are expected, on current evidence, to keep failing even after PR #441's real fixes -- for reasons named here (missing debian/ dir + missing dispatch; placeholder GCP registry + missing secret) that are themselves new, real, distinctly-scoped follow-on obligations, not yet attempted. The detector (once merged) will make this directly observable on the next real tag rather than requiring another manual audit pass." ;
    retrofit:evidenceUpdate2026_07_22c "release-debian.yml's two named gaps CLOSED (1 of the 2 targets named in evidenceUpdate2026_07_22b as still-broken-after-PR-441); docker-build-push.yml's GCP registry/secret gap is untouched and remains open, named explicitly so it is not conflated with this closure.\n\n(1) Missing debian/ directory: created a real, complete Debian source package (debian/control, debian/changelog, debian/rules, debian/copyright, debian/source/format = \"3.0 (native)\" -- chosen because this repo packages directly from its own tree with no separate upstream tarball, avoiding the whole missing-orig.tar.gz failure class a non-native/quilt format would introduce). debian/rules skips cargo build entirely (override_dh_auto_build is a no-op) and only stages the binary scripts/build-debian-package.sh's own Gate 4 already built, matching that script's existing real structure rather than fighting it.\n\n(2) Two more real bugs found and fixed in scripts/build-debian-package.sh while making it work end-to-end, beyond the debian/ directory itself: Gate 5 hardcoded /home/user/ggen/target/release/ggen (an absolute path from whichever machine originally authored this script -- the real GitHub Actions runner checks out at /home/runner/work/ggen/ggen, so this line would have failed even after the debian/ directory existed; masked until now because Gate 2 always failed first). Fixed to a path relative to the repo root, matching every other gate. Separately, four hardcoded \"5.0.2\"/\"5.0.2-1_amd64\" references (matching neither this repo's real ~26.x version scheme nor debian/source/format's native-package convention, which carries no separate debian-revision suffix) -- replaced with a real Gate 8 that derives VERSION from GITHUB_REF_NAME when running in CI (the tag being released) or Cargo.toml's workspace version as a local/manual fallback, ARCH from `dpkg --print-architecture` (not a hardcoded \"amd64\"), and dynamically rewrites debian/changelog's top entry to match before debuild runs -- the same root-cause class of bug (a hardcoded value standing in for something that should be derived from the real release context) already fixed twice this session for docker-build-push.yml's now() and homebrew-release.yml's version-source. Noted, not fixed (genuinely non-functional, not a scope-discipline call): scripts/install-ggen.sh also hardcodes VERSION=\"5.0.2\", but only as a local temp-download-filename label (/tmp/ggen_${VERSION}_amd64.deb) that the actual install logic never depends on for correctness -- confirmed by reading Gate 5-7 of that script directly, left alone.\n\n(3) Dispatch wiring added, mirroring the exact pattern already proven live for homebrew-release.yml (PR #441): release-debian.yml gained a workflow_dispatch trigger (no explicit tag input needed here, unlike homebrew-release.yml, since scripts/build-debian-package.sh reads GITHUB_REF_NAME directly and dispatching with --ref <tag> already sets that correctly); release.yml gained a new dispatch-release-debian job, needs:[build-release], calling `gh workflow run release-debian.yml --ref \"$TAG\"` right after the binary release completes -- byte-for-byte the same GITHUB_TOKEN-exception mechanism already validated working for homebrew-release.yml's own dispatch.\n\nVerification performed, honestly scoped -- real tooling used where available, gap disclosed where not: no Debian packaging tools exist on this session's own machine (macOS; confirmed `debuild`/`dpkg-buildpackage`/`devscripts`/`debhelper` all absent). Installed real `dpkg` 1.23.7 via Homebrew (debhelper itself has no macOS port and could not be installed) and a real `python-debian` in an isolated venv, then used the ACTUAL parsers debuild/dpkg-buildpackage rely on internally, not just visual inspection: `dpkg-parsechangelog` on debian/changelog -- real parse, correct Source/Version/Distribution/Urgency/Maintainer/Date fields, exit 0. `python-debian`'s Deb822 parser on debian/control -- real parse, exactly 2 stanzas (Source, Package) with every intended field present and correctly typed. `python-debian`'s Changelog parser re-run against the build script's OWN dynamic-generation logic (not just the static seed file) with a real derived VERSION and real `date -R` output -- parses cleanly, confirming the actual runtime code path this pass added, not just the file it left behind. shellcheck clean on the rewritten build script (0 warnings, including two pre-existing SC2086 quoting issues fixed as a trivial bonus). This repo's own scripts/ci/validate-workflows.py: [PASS] release.yml, [PASS] release-debian.yml (the run's sole [FAIL], tf-acceptance.yml, is pre-existing and untouched).\n\nHONEST LIMITATION, same discipline as every release-workflow fix this session: the full debuild/dh build chain (debian/rules' `dh $@` sequence, the actual `.deb` assembly) could not be exercised locally -- debhelper has no macOS port, and this workflow only runs on a real tag push or workflow_dispatch against a real tag, which this session is not authorized to trigger without an explicit `!` command. What WAS verified is real (the two most syntax-sensitive files, control and changelog, parse correctly under the actual tools that will process them; the version-derivation logic that fixes the root cause runs and produces correct output) -- what remains unverified is the debhelper build sequence itself, disclosed plainly rather than assumed. Deferred to the next naturally-occurring release cycle, same as PR #441's three fixes.\n\nStanding remains Blocking: docker-build-push.yml's GCP-registry-placeholder + missing-secret gap (named in evidenceUpdate2026_07_22b) is untouched by this pass and is now the SPOF's most concrete remaining open item, alongside rollback itself (still correctly out of scope pending human authorization)." ;
    retrofit:evidenceUpdate2026_07_22d "docker-build-push.yml's GCP-registry gap CLOSED (the last of the 2 targets named in evidenceUpdate2026_07_22b as still-broken-after-PR-441) -- this pass removes the non-functional path rather than provisioning real infrastructure, a design choice made under DESIGN_UNCERTAINTY_LAW, reasoned explicitly below, not defaulted to.\n\nGoverning invariant derived from the evidence, not assumed: REGISTRY_GCP: artifacts.example.com is an IANA documentation domain (confirmed via dig/nslookup -- no A record, ever), and GCP_ARTIFACT_REGISTRY_KEY has never existed as a repo secret at any point checked this session (`gh api repos/.../actions/secrets` -> zero secrets configured) -- this was aspirational scaffolding that never had real infrastructure behind it, not a currently load-bearing capability regressing. Two designs evaluated: (A) leave as-is, bounded-accepted-risk, since fixing needs a real secret -- rejected: the target would keep failing forever with no path to ever going green, and unlike a true externally-gated item (which becomes actionable the moment authorization arrives), NOTHING short of provisioning real GCP infrastructure (an org-level decision this session cannot make or evidence) would ever fix it, so \"bounded accepted risk\" would in practice mean \"permanently red, never revisited.\" (B, chosen) remove the non-functional GCP path, keep GHCR (already real, already using the working secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN) -- makes the target genuinely achievable today, at the cost of narrowing published-registry scope from two to one. Chosen because GHCR-only is a real, working, smaller thing beats a permanently-broken aspiration to two registries; re-adding real GCP publishing remains possible later and is now a clean, well-scoped external-actuation obligation (needs an actual GCP project/registry + a real service-account key as a repo secret) rather than a silent, permanent failure.\n\nScope of the fix, once GCP's presence was traced through the whole file (not just the two build-job login/tag references named in evidenceUpdate2026_07_22b): removed the GCP login step and GCP entry from the metadata images: list in BOTH build-controller and build-cli; removed REGISTRY_GCP from the workflow's env: block entirely; updated scan-images' two Trivy image-ref values from the GCP path to the real GHCR path (registry/repository_owner/image -- the GCP path never included repository_owner, so this was a real path-shape correction, not just a hostname swap); removed the GCP `docker login` line from sign-and-sbom's \"Log in to registries\" step and updated its syft/cosign commands (SBOM generation, image signing, SBOM attestation attach -- 6 commands total) to the same real GHCR path. Also removed a genuinely dead, unused `REGISTRY: artifacts.example.com` env var from semantic-release.yml (declared once, referenced nowhere else in that file -- confirmed via grep -- a small, same-pattern, in-scope cleanup, not a new investigation).\n\nReal, additional gap found and fixed while making this actually work, beyond what evidenceUpdate2026_07_22b named: scan-images had NO docker/login-action step at all, in either the original GCP design or a naive GHCR-only fix -- Docker credentials are per-job, not shared across jobs in GitHub Actions, so build-controller/build-cli's own login never carried over. Images pushed via GITHUB_TOKEN default to private visibility, so pulling one to scan it always needed its own fresh login; this was latent (never observed failing) purely because the workflow never survived long enough to reach this job before. Added the same GHCR login step already proven in the build jobs.\n\nDISCLOSED, deliberately NOT fixed in this pass -- a separate, real finding, not silently noticed and dropped: .github/CI_CD_PIPELINE.md and .github/CICD_IMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md both extensively document GCP Artifact Registry publishing as a working, complete (\"✅\") capability -- now false. Investigated whether to do a narrow correction of just the GCP lines, and found the docs' problem is broader than GCP specifically: the SAME files also mark \"✅ Automated Rollback: Health-check-triggered automatic rollbacks\" (directly contradicting retrofit:PartialPublishRollbackUnknown's own confirmed-absent rollback mechanism), \"✅ GitOps: Declarative infrastructure management with Flux CD v2\", and \"✅ Automatic Slack/GitHub notifications ready\" -- none independently verified this session, several already known-false. A narrow GCP-only edit would have left equally-unverified adjacent claims looking newly-authoritative by contrast, which is its own kind of misleading. Left both docs untouched rather than partially, inconsistently correct them; a real, dedicated documentation-accuracy pass over these two files (auditing every \"✅\" claim against actual repository evidence, not just the GCP ones) is a genuine, separate, not-yet-scoped future obligation, named here so it is not lost.\n\nVerification: python3 -c \"import yaml\" clean on both modified files; this repo's own scripts/ci/validate-workflows.py: [PASS] docker-build-push.yml, [PASS] semantic-release.yml (the run's sole [FAIL], tf-acceptance.yml, is pre-existing and untouched); grep confirms zero remaining functional REGISTRY_GCP/GCP_ARTIFACT_REGISTRY_KEY references anywhere in docker-build-push.yml (only historical-context comments remain). Same honest limitation as every release-workflow fix this session: this workflow only runs on a real tag push or workflow_dispatch against a real tag, and this session is not authorized to trigger one without an explicit `!` -- the GHCR-only path is reasoned and YAML-valid but not yet observed green on a real run, deferred to the next naturally-occurring release cycle.\n\nStanding on retrofit:PartialPublishRollbackUnknown remains Blocking: both concretely-named target-level gaps from evidenceUpdate2026_07_22b are now closed (release-debian.yml, docker-build-push.yml), but the SPOF's own actual named concern -- partial-publish rollback -- was never in scope for either fix and remains entirely unbuilt, correctly deferred pending explicit human authorization per this SPOF's own hard constraint. The newly-disclosed CI_CD_PIPELINE.md/CICD_IMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md documentation-accuracy problem is a real, separate, not-yet-scoped obligation, distinct from this SPOF." ;
    retrofit:evidenceUpdate2026_07_22e "REAL PROGRESS on the SPOF's own actual named concern (partial-publish rollback) for the first time -- 4 prior evidence passes correctly deferred an automated rollback ENGINE as needing human authorization, but had not yet applied DESIGN_UNCERTAINTY_LAW's own requirement to find the smallest design closing real value without that detour. Found one: extended scripts/ci/check-partial-publish.sh (the read-only detector built in evidenceUpdate2026_07_22b) with a Remediation Runbook section -- when a target FAILs, the script now prints the exact `gh workflow run` command a human operator would run to re-publish just that target for the same tag, using each target's own already-live workflow_dispatch trigger (confirmed by reading each file's real `on:` block, not assumed: release.yml/homebrew-release.yml take a `tag` input, release-debian.yml/docker-build-push.yml take none beyond `--ref`). Text generation only -- zero new mutating `gh`/`git`/`docker` calls added; the READ-ONLY hard constraint in this script's own header comment and in detect-partial-publish.yml's `permissions: contents: read` are both unchanged.\n\nTwo designs evaluated per DESIGN_UNCERTAINTY_LAW, not defaulted to: (A) build the actual rollback engine -- an automated system that, on FAIL, itself deletes/retags/republishes already-published state -- rejected, unchanged reasoning from every prior pass: retracting a real release/image/formula a user may have already pulled is exactly the class of hard-to-reverse, externally-visible action this session's operating rules gate on explicit human sign-off, and no authorization packet for it exists yet (checked docs/retrofit/ggen/authorization-packets.md directly -- only AP-001/AP-002 exist, neither covers this). (B, chosen) the remediation-runbook extension described above -- closes real operational value (a human responding to a real FAIL no longer has to reconstruct the correct dispatch command by hand or by reading 4 separate workflow files) without crossing into the authorization-gated action class at all, since 'print the command that re-runs an already-existing, already-authorized dispatch path' is categorically different from 'mutate already-published state.'\n\nVerified: `bash -n` and `shellcheck` both clean (0 warnings). Ran live against two real current tags: v26.15.1 and v26.7.48 -- both genuinely FAIL on release.yml today (missing all binary/sha256 assets; consistent with evidenceUpdate2026_07_22b's earlier finding that recent auto-bumped tags haven't actually been dispatched through release.yml), correctly producing a Remediation Runbook block with the real `gh workflow run release.yml --ref <tag> -f tag=<tag>` command, while the other 3 PENDING targets on the same run correctly get NO remediation entry (PENDING is not a definitive failure -- unchanged invariant from the original script). detect-partial-publish.yml needed no changes: read in full, confirmed it only pipes the script's whole stdout to `$GITHUB_STEP_SUMMARY` via `tee -a` with no structured parsing the new Markdown section could break.\n\nStanding remains Blocking, correctly: this closes real value on the SPOF's own concern but does not resolve it -- a human still has to notice a FAIL and manually run the printed command; nothing here is automatic. What changed is that the SPOF's remaining gap now has a clean shape: automated remediation (having the runbook step itself invoke the command, or a scheduled re-check-and-retry loop) is the next real increment, and it WOULD need the authorization AP-001/AP-002-style packet this pass avoided needing -- named here as the precise next obligation, not a vague 'rollback is hard' placeholder." .

retrofit:AutomatedRollbackAndChangelogWorkflowsParseBroken a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "automated-rollback.yml + generate-release-notes.yml -- both fail on every real trigger due to workflow-file-parse / bash-syntax bugs, unrelated to the 5 targets retrofit:PartialPublishRollbackUnknown already tracks" ;
    retrofit:standing "Blocking" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:ReleasePath ;
    retrofit:evidence "Surfaced while pursuing the CI_CD_PIPELINE.md/CICD_IMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md documentation-accuracy audit named as a future obligation in retrofit:PartialPublishRollbackUnknown's evidenceUpdate2026_07_22d: read CICD_IMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md's claims in full (485 lines, dated 2026-01-25, `Status: Complete`, `Version: 1.0.0 Production-Ready`) and checked each named file's existence directly. ci-complete.yml, gitops-sync-flux.yml, helm-validation.yml, infra/flux/ confirmed absent -- already-known-false claims, not re-litigated here. automated-rollback.yml, generate-release-notes.yml, scripts/ci-setup.sh confirmed present -- but two of the three, on inspection, are broken in a way distinct from being merely undocumented-as-nonfunctional: they fail their OWN mechanics on every real trigger, independent of whether the K8s/changelog features they implement are otherwise a good idea. Neither is one of the 5 targets retrofit:PartialPublishRollbackUnknown's evidence already covers (publish-registry.yml, publish-candidate.yml, homebrew-release.yml, release-debian.yml, docker-build-push.yml); a new SPOF is the honest home for this rather than force-fitting it into a differently-scoped one.\n\n(1) automated-rollback.yml: `gh run list --workflow=automated-rollback.yml` shows repeated `event: push` failures with timestamps matching every recent push to main, despite the file's own `on:` block declaring only workflow_dispatch (schedule already disabled via a pre-existing header comment: `# schedule disabled -- no Kubernetes cluster deployed`). `gh api .../runs/29955887092 --jq '{name, conclusion, event, jobs_url}'` returns `name: \".github/workflows/automated-rollback.yml\"` -- the literal file path, not the declared `name:` field -- with `jobs: []`, and `gh run view` reports \"This run likely failed because of a workflow file issue.\": the exact same workflow-file-parse-failure signature already root-caused twice this session for docker-build-push.yml's `now()` bug (evidenceUpdate2026_07_22) and independently for this file. Root cause, found by reading the file: two occurrences of `${{ secrets[KUBECONFIG_VAR] }}` -- indexing the secrets context with a shell-computed variable, which is not valid GitHub Actions expression syntax (secret references must be static/literal so GitHub can scan the file and redact secret values from logs; a runtime-computed key defeats that and fails the ENTIRE file's schema validation at parse time, before any `on:` filter is even evaluated -- explaining why it fires and fails on every push regardless of the declared trigger). Fixed both occurrences (execute-rollback and post-rollback-verification jobs) with a static ternary expression selecting between two literal secret references (`secrets.KUBECONFIG_PROD` / `secrets.KUBECONFIG_STAGING`) passed via a step-level `env:` block. A third, pre-existing `secrets.KUBECONFIG_PROD` reference in the health-check job was ALREADY static (not this bug) and is gated behind the disabled schedule trigger -- left untouched. Separately noted, not fixed: this file's own domain vocabulary (`helm history tai -n production`, `kubectl rollout status deployment/tai-controller`) names a service `tai`/`tai-controller`, not this repo's real image names (`catalog-controller`/`ggen-cli` per docker-build-push.yml) -- independent confirmation this is vendored/foreign boilerplate never adapted to this repo, a real but separately-scoped concern from the parse bug (whether this K8s rollback concept should exist here at all, given there is no deployed Kubernetes cluster, is a design question this pass does not attempt to resolve).\n\n(2) generate-release-notes.yml: `gh run list` shows exactly one historical run ever (v26.7.2, 2026-07-02, `event: release`, failure) -- unlike automated-rollback.yml, this one shows its correctly-declared job name (`Generate Release Notes from Commits`), meaning this is NOT a parse-time failure but a real runtime bug reached mid-execution. `gh run view 28626920699 --log-failed` shows steps 'Determine release tag' and 'Get previous release' both succeeded, then 'Generate changelog' failed immediately: `/home/runner/work/_temp/<id>.sh: line 22: syntax error in conditional expression` / `Process completed with exit code 2`. Reproduced byte-for-byte locally (`bash /tmp/repro.sh` -> identical `syntax error in conditional expression: unexpected token \\`]'\\`` at the same relative line): the four commit-type checks (`elif [[ \"$MSG\" =~ ^feat(\\(.+\\))?:[ ] ]]; then`, and the same pattern for fix/perf/chore) put a `[ ]` character class -- intended to match one literal space after the colon -- directly against the closing `]]` of the `[[ ]]` test, which bash's parser cannot handle (a single-token-boundary ambiguity, confirmed real and reproducing on this session's own bash 5.3.3, not a version-specific quirk). Since bash parses the whole `run:` block as one script before executing any of it, this aborted the ENTIRE step immediately -- no changelog was ever generated on that run, and (having zero runs since) the bug was never re-triggered to be re-discovered. Fixed by replacing `[ ]` with an escaped literal space (`\\ `), semantically identical (still requires exactly one space after the colon) but not adjacent to `]]` in a way the parser chokes on -- verified against 10 real conventional-commit-message test cases locally (feat/feat-scoped/feat-breaking/feat-scoped-breaking/fix/fix-scoped/perf/chore/non-matching/missing-space), all resolving to the correct bucket, zero syntax errors.\n\nVerification performed, both fixes: `python3 -c \"import yaml; yaml.safe_load(...)\"` clean on both files; `bash -n` clean on the actual extracted `run:` block text (not a paraphrase) for generate-release-notes.yml's Generate-changelog step; this repo's own scripts/ci/validate-workflows.py: [PASS] automated-rollback.yml, [PASS] generate-release-notes.yml (the run's sole [FAIL], tf-acceptance.yml, is pre-existing -- confirmed via `git diff --stat origin/main` showing zero changes to that file on this branch -- and unrelated to either fix). HONEST LIMITATION, same discipline as every other release-workflow fix this session: neither fix has been observed on a real trigger -- automated-rollback.yml only runs on workflow_dispatch or the disabled schedule, generate-release-notes.yml only runs on a real published release or workflow_dispatch against one, and this session is not authorized to trigger either without an explicit `!` command. Standing correctly remains Blocking, not restood Accepted, pending that observation -- matching the exact precedent already established for retrofit:ReleaseGateBrokenForWeeks (kept Blocking through multiple real fixes until an actual green run was observed) rather than the weaker bar of 'the diff looks right.' Next action: observe the next real workflow_dispatch or release-published trigger for either file; restand to Accepted only then. The whole-file-parse-failure root cause (an invalid expression anywhere in a file silently breaking every job regardless of trigger filter) is now confirmed to have hit 3 separate files this session (docker-build-push.yml's now(), automated-rollback.yml's secrets[...], and this evidence's own generate-release-notes.yml bash-syntax variant of the same failure class) -- worth a future session considering a lint rule or CI job that renders/dry-runs every workflow's `run:` blocks through `bash -n`, since scripts/ci/validate-workflows.py's existing YAML-structural checks did not and could not have caught either of the two bugs this pass found (both are valid YAML; the defects are in GitHub's expression-syntax rules and in bash's own grammar, one layer below what a YAML parser sees)." .

retrofit:GithubPagesEnvironmentStaleMasterPolicy a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "publish-registry.yml ('Deploy Documentation to GitHub Pages') fails on every push -- 3 stacked problems, 1 fixed, 1 authorization-gated, 1 disclosed as a real documentation-scope decision" ;
    retrofit:standing "Blocking" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:ReleasePath ;
    retrofit:evidence "Investigated as a new lead, initially misidentified (this evidence's own first draft named the wrong file, deploy-docs.yml, as the failing workflow based on a run-name match alone; corrected once the actual file, publish-registry.yml, was confirmed via `grep -l 'Deploy Documentation to GitHub Pages' .github/workflows/*.yml` -- deploy-docs.yml has a different `name:` field, 'Deploy Documentation', and is a separate, near-duplicate workflow with its own issues, not this one).\n\nThree independent, stacked problems found by reading the file and its dependencies against real repo state:\n\n(1) Every run fails in ~2 seconds, before any step executes: 'Branch main is not allowed to deploy to github-pages due to environment protection rules.' Root cause, confirmed via `gh api repos/.../environments/github-pages` and `.../deployment-branch-policies`: the github-pages environment's custom branch policy names only 'master' (environment created 2025-10-09) -- this repo's real default branch is 'main', a stale rename gap. NOT fixed here: mutating environment protection rules is a permission-adjacent repo-settings change, same class as AP-001's branch protection -- written up as AP-004 in docs/retrofit/ggen/authorization-packets.md (exact gh api POST/DELETE calls, rollback, post-checks) and ctl:AP-004 in ../controller/obligations.ttl, both EXTERNALLY_GATED pending an explicit user ! command.\n\n(2) FIXED, no authorization needed: the job's bespoke `dtolnay/rust-toolchain@... toolchain: stable` step is the exact same class already found and fixed twice this session (release.yml PR #426, marketplace-test.yml this session, see retrofit:BespokeToolchainSetupBypassesSccache) -- ignores the pinned nightly toolchain, never provisions [patch.crates-io] siblings, never installs sccache. Currently masked by (1) always failing first. Swapped for the proven ./.github/actions/setup-ggen-build composite action.\n\n(3) NOT fixed, genuinely a larger, disclosed-not-attempted scope: even past (1) and (2), the 'Build documentation' step (`mdbook build docs`) would fail. docs/book.toml declares `src = \"src\"`, but docs/src/ was deleted 2026-03-31 (commit e611373, 'delete 1,892 stale MD/TXT files') and never restored -- confirmed via `git log --diff-filter=D -- 'docs/src/*'`. This workflow was itself last touched 2026-06-20 ('ci: harden operational CD workflows'), three months AFTER that deletion, without anyone noticing the source tree it builds had ceased to exist. book/ (this repo's other, actively-maintained mdbook project, subject of this session's earlier book/ggen.lock fix) is NOT a drop-in replacement -- its own book.toml title is 'ggen: Manufacturing Level Five Packs', a narrower, different-scoped topic than this workflow's 'ggen Documentation' name implies. deploy-docs.yml (the near-duplicate workflow noted above) independently references the same deleted docs/src/ via `cd docs && mdbook build`, via a different, older gh-pages-branch deployment mechanism (peaceiris/actions-gh-pages, not this workflow's Actions-native environment-gated deploy-pages) -- both broken for the same underlying reason. Deciding whether to redirect this content to book/, restore docs/src/, or retire one or both of these near-duplicate workflows is a real documentation-scope/product decision requiring judgment about what ggen's public docs site should actually contain -- not a mechanical bug, and not attempted in this pass.\n\nVerification of what WAS fixed: python3 -c \"import yaml\" clean; this repo's own scripts/ci/validate-workflows.py: [PASS] publish-registry.yml (the run's sole [FAIL], tf-acceptance.yml, is pre-existing and untouched). Standing correctly remains Blocking -- this pass makes real, disclosed, honest progress (one root cause fixed, one packaged for authorization) but the workflow does not yet succeed end-to-end and is not claimed to." .

retrofit:ConstitutionDescriptiveMirrorOnly a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "ccn:Law facts consulted but decision-inert by design -- confirmed, evidence corrected" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:ConstitutionPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "CORRECTED MECHANISM, conclusion still holds, re-verified 2026-07-21: original evidence text ('write_receipt independent of ggen-constitution-pack') is now factually stale -- merged commit 8c9edb3e4 (PR #316) added a real ccn:Law/ccn:mechanized SPARQL query to sync.rs::write_receipt, emitting one AdmissionItem per constitutional law found. But the code deliberately hardcodes AdmissionDecision::Admitted on BOTH branches (mechanized true or false), with an explicit comment: 'it must not flip the derived Andon level (that would overclaim a live verification that doesn't exist)'. praxis-core::law::DefaultLaw::admit remains fully independent of ggen-constitution-pack (zero references), confirmed unchanged. Net: facts are consulted and mirrored into the receipt's obligation list (a real, if inert, improvement over pure disconnection), but by design still never change the pass/fail decision or Andon level -- the SPOF's substantive claim holds, Accepted standing correct given this is an honestly-disclosed, deliberate non-enforcement choice (the same discipline as the ccn:mechanized=false laws), not a hidden defect." .

retrofit:LawXIIFalseCitation a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "Law XII engine-independence citation -- RESOLVED, corrected not fabricated" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:ConstitutionPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "RESOLVED 2026-07-21: crates/ggen-engine/tests/reasoner_independence_e2e.rs is a REAL file (both_engines_sync_a_gated_pack_to_identical_outputs, violating_fixture_is_refused_under_both_engines -- both run and PASS 2026-07-21) proving exactly the cited property. The prior 'zero matches' finding searched for a literal function name equal to the file name; the file/module itself was never missing. .specify/memory/constitution.md's citation and packs/ggen-constitution-pack/ontology.ttl's LawXII ccn:note both corrected to name the real file and its two actual function names precisely." .

retrofit:UnmechanizedLawsDisclosed a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "9 laws (not 3) explicitly mechanized=false, every one with a named gap" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:ConstitutionPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "CORRECTED count via direct read, packs/ggen-constitution-pack/ontology.ttl: 9 of 14 laws are mechanized=false (I, V, VI, VII, VIII, IX, XI, XIII, XIV), not the 3 (VII, XI, XIV) this SPOF's label originally named -- an undercount, not an overcount. Verified EVERY SINGLE mechanized=false law carries an explicit ccn:note disclosing exactly what's missing (e.g. Law I: no dedicated cycle-rejection test found; Law XI: sync.rs:1857 hardcodes andon=Green, named as an ACTIVE DIVERGENCE pending the v2 epoch migration; Law XIV: no fixed-point-closure test exists yet) -- zero silent gaps among the 9. Accepted standing is correct and, if anything, more strongly earned than the original label suggested: this is unusually thorough self-disclosure, not corner-cutting." .

retrofit:FleetCensusObservationOnly a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "Fleet census has no confirmed reconciliation loop against live fleet state" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:FleetManagementPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "BOUNDED ACCEPTED RISK, evidence-based, 2026-07-21: confirmed docs/gh-terraform/FLEET-CENSUS.md (408 lines, ~359 external repos across chatmangpt-org/EpicGames/etc.) is honestly self-labeled 'OBSERVATION, NOT DESIRED STATE' with a real generation timestamp -- it makes no currency claim a reader could be misled by, which is the actual false-standing risk this class of SPOF exists to catch, and that risk does not exist here. A real re-run-and-diff reconciliation loop against live fleet state is a substantial, distinctly-scoped engineering effort (359 external repos, none of them ggen itself) genuinely orthogonal to ggen's own self-retrofit correctness (FleetManagementPath does not intersect SelfGenerationPath/ConstitutionPath/ReleasePath, the paths this session's generations have been closing). Accepting as bounded risk rather than building it now: scope=documented staleness of a labeled snapshot only, no false-currency claim possible, failure consequence=a stale snapshot informing a future fleet decision (mitigated by the explicit label), owner=a future, separately-scoped fleet-reconciliation generation, review trigger=before any fleet-wide tier assignment or batch actuation is proposed from this data." .

retrofit:FleetCloudIdentityUnverified a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "Sole cloud-actuation identity for fleet-management -- genuinely unverifiable from this environment" ;
    retrofit:standing "Unknown" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:FleetManagementPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "RE-CONFIRMED 2026-07-21: no cloud IAM access exists in this environment, then or now -- genuinely unverifiable, not merely unchecked. docs/gh-terraform/FLEET-CENSUS.md (the one adjacent artifact) is a read-only census of GitHub repository settings, not cloud/IAM infrastructure -- does not touch this claim. Stays Unknown honestly: this is not a bounded-accepted-risk (the risk's actual magnitude can't be assessed without the access this environment lacks) nor a repair (nothing to fix without first observing). Terminal state: named, correctly Unknown, requires either cloud IAM access being granted to a future investigation or explicit acceptance that this remains permanently unverifiable from a repo-only vantage point." .

retrofit:CrossCuttingSingleAdmin a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "seanchatmangpt is a SPOF across PR, release, and fleet-management -- EXTERNAL ACTUATION PACKETS (partial) + named residual gap" ;
    retrofit:standing "Blocking" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:PullRequestPath, retrofit:ReleasePath, retrofit:FleetManagementPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "TERMINAL STATE REACHED 2026-07-21, with an honestly-named residual: root cause (sole admin account) is addressed by AP-002 (pending a user-supplied second-admin identity -- a genuine external trust decision, not derivable). PullRequestPath leg: partially addressed once AP-001+AP-002 both execute (branch protection + a real second reviewer). ReleasePath leg (tag-push/workflow_dispatch exposure on release.yml): NOT addressed by AP-001/AP-002 at all -- GitHub tag-protection rules are a separate settings surface, would need its own authorization packet, not yet authored (named as a follow-on, not fabricated here). FleetManagementPath leg: NOT addressed -- tracked separately as the genuinely-Unknown retrofit:FleetCloudIdentityUnverified. Stays Blocking honestly: 2 of 3 legs remain open even after AP-001/AP-002, correctly not overclaimed as fully closed by pointing at those two packets alone." .

retrofit:DependabotNpmAdvisoriesUnpatched a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "11 open GitHub Dependabot alerts (npm ecosystem, 5 critical/2 high/4 moderate) on 3 committed lockfiles" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:GenerationPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "DISCOVERED 2026-07-21 via `gh api repos/seanchatmangpt/ggen/dependabot/alerts` (surfaced incidentally by a `git push` warning during the tcps-core-pack force:true fix, not part of any prior sweep). All 11 alerts are npm ecosystem (vitest/vite/js-yaml/postcss transitive deps), zero overlap with `cargo audit` (which already passes in CI and covers the actual Rust runtime surface). Root-caused to 3 committed package-lock.json files: examples/archive/sparql-construct-city, examples/archive/bree-semantic-scheduler (both dormant demo apps under O-6-hygiene's already-tracked examples/archive/ cruft), and marketplace/packages/io.ggen.nextjs.ontology-crud (a real but CI-unexercised marketplace demo package, last touched 2026-06-12, confirmed via `grep -rl` against .github/workflows/ that none of these 3 paths are referenced by any workflow). REPAIRED (partial, real, verified) same cycle: `npm audit fix` (non-force) applied to all 3, confirmed via `npm audit --json` vulnerability counts dropping (12->6, 12->6, 13->8) and `npm install --package-lock-only` from a clean node_modules producing byte-identical output (no drift beyond the intended fix) -- committed alongside this restanding. Residual, deliberately NOT force-fixed: the remaining vulnerabilities require `npm audit fix --force` (a vitest major-version bump and a next.js bump outside marketplace/packages/io.ggen.nextjs.ontology-crud's stated dependency range) -- refused this cycle under the same discipline as tcps-core-pack's per-file review: no CI harness exists in this repo to verify these apps still build/run after an unverified breaking bump, and blind-committing an unverified major-version change would itself be a fabricated-completion violation (Evidence-First Principle). Stands Accepted, not Blocking: these are dev-only tooling deps (vitest UI server, vite dev server) in code no CI path reaches and no shipped Rust binary depends on -- real public disclosure-surface risk, but bounded blast radius, and the safe half of the fix is already applied. Terminal remediation options for a future cycle, not fabricated here: (a) `npm audit fix --force` + a real manual `npm run build`/`npm test` verification pass per app, or (b) delete these 3 dead demo trees entirely as part of O-6-hygiene's already-scoped examples/archive/ deletion-ledger pass, which would remove the disclosure surface outright rather than chase it." .

retrofit:ReceiptctlLockDriftGuardFailure a retrofit:SPOF ;
    rdfs:label "guard-pack-proofs fails locally: examples/receiptctl's ggen.lock content hash for chicago-tdd-tools-pack no longer matches the pack on disk" ;
    retrofit:standing "Accepted" ;
    retrofit:affects retrofit:GenerationPath ;
    retrofit:evidence "DISCOVERED and REPAIRED 2026-07-21 (retrofit/ggen-self-g6 discovery, retrofit/ggen-self-g7 repair). Discovered running a full `just pre-commit` locally as an extra-caution check before merging a large O-6-hygiene deletion PR (#363) -- not surfaced by CI (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`'s Check job runs only `cargo check --workspace --exclude ggen-lsp`, never `just pre-commit` or any guard-*.sh script). Root-caused via `git log` on both paths going back past this session's own commit range: 5 of the 6 packs examples/receiptctl wires (chicago-tdd-tools-pack, clap-noun-verb-pack, wasm4pm-algorithms-pack, wasm4pm-cognition-pack, wasm4pm-compat-pack) were correctly fixed in the ORIGINAL 8-pack cross_pack_matrix force:true cleanup (this session's own Generation 2/3, commit 2f255951b/PR #360), the 6th (wasm4pm-facts-pack) in this session's own Generation 5 -- but examples/receiptctl's committed ggen.lock, a separate real consumer of all 6 packs, was never re-synced after any of that work, so ALL 6 hashes had drifted, not just chicago-tdd-tools-pack (the error only reports the first mismatch it finds). Repaired per the tool's own [FM-PACK-008] remediation ('delete ggen.lock to intentionally re-lock'): backed up the old lock, deleted it, ran a real `ggen sync run` to regenerate all 6 hashes against current (correct) on-disk content. Verified: a second `ggen sync run --dry-run` passes clean; `cargo test` in examples/receiptctl (150 tests across 14 binaries) all pass; `git diff` confirms ONLY ggen.lock changed, zero generated output files affected. Accepted, not merely closed-and-forgotten: the underlying content was always correct, only lock metadata was stale, and it's now current." .
